SIMPLE: experience
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Experience
<hw>Ex*pe"ri*ence</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*p⟦emac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦eit⟧ns)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>exp⟦eacute⟧rience</ets>, L.
<ets>experientia</ets>, tr. <ets>experiens</ets>,
<ets>experientis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>experiri</ets>,
<ets>expertus</ets>, to try; <ets>ex</ets> out + the root of
<ets>peritus</ets> experienced. See <er>Peril</er>, and cf.
<er>Expert</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Trial, as a test or
experiment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She caused him to make <qex>experience</qex>⟦br⟧
Upon wild beasts.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The effect upon the judgment or feelings produced by
any event, whether witnessed or participated in; personal and direct
impressions as contrasted with description or fancies; personal
acquaintance; actual enjoyment or suffering.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Guided by
other's <xex>experiences</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have but one lamp by which my feet are guided, and that is the
lamp of <qex>experience</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>P. Henry</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>To most men experience</qex> is like the stern lights of a
ship, which illumine only the track it has passed.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the consuls . . . came in . . . they knew soon by
<qex>experience</qex> how slenderly guarded against danger the majesty
of rulers is where force is wanting.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those that undertook the religion of our Savior upon his
preaching, had no <qex>experience</qex> of it.</q>
<rj><qau>Sharp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An act of knowledge, one or more, by which single
facts or general truths are ascertained; experimental or inductive
knowledge; hence, implying skill, facility, or practical wisdom gained
by personal knowledge, feeling or action; <as>as, a king without
<ex>experience</ex> of war</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whence hath the mind all the materials of reason and knowledge? To
this I answer in one word, from <qex>experience</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Experience</qex> may be acquired in two ways; either, first
by noticing facts without any attempt to influence the frequency of
their occurrence or to vary the circumstances under which they occur;
this is <qex>observation</qex>; or, secondly, by putting in action
causes or agents over which we have control, and purposely varying their
combinations, and noticing what effects take place; this is
<qex>experiment</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Herschel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Experience</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Experience
<hw>Ex*pe"ri*ence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Experienced</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*p⟦emac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦eit⟧nst)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Experiencing</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*p⟦emac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦eit⟧n*s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make practical acquaintance with; to try personally; to prove by
use or trial; to have trial of; to have the lot or fortune of; to have
befall one; to be affected by; to feel; <as>as, to <ex>experience</ex>
pain or pleasure; to <ex>experience</ex> poverty; to <ex>experience</ex>
a change of views.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The partial failure and disappointment which he had
<qex>experienced</qex> in India.</q> <rj><qau>Thirwall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exercise; to train by practice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The youthful sailors thus with early care⟦br⟧
Their arms <qex>experience</qex>, and for sea prepare.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To experience religion</b></col> <fld>(Theol.)</fld>,
<cd>to become a convert to the doctrines of Christianity; to yield to
the power of religious truth.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>experienced</ent>⟦br⟧
